<FIRST>u i BC-Khomeini     06-04 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Khomeini,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Dies at 86; Iran Meets to Map Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the founder
of Iran's Islamic Republic, died in a Tehran hospital at age 86,
and Iran's Parliament met in emergency session Sunday to read his
final plans for the nation's future.
   Khomeini died Saturday with the question of who will succeed him
unresolved. Iranian opposition leaders in exile said the country
could be plunged into political turmoil.
   Hundreds of thousands of Iranians dressed in black converged on
Khomeini's residence in the north Tehran suburb of Jamaran after
news of his death was announced.
   Tehran television, monitored in Nicosia, showed men and women
clad in head-to-toe black chadors beating on their heads and chests
hysterically in a traditional show of grief.
   Many waved life-size portraits of their revolutionary patriarch.
Others chanted: ``Sorrow, sorrow is this day ... Khomeini the idol
smasher is with God this day.''
   State-run television screened old films of the black-turbaned,
white-bearded Khomeini on his return from exile in 1979, addressing
crowds of worshippers, or lying in his hospital bed after
undergoing an operation May 23 for bleeding in his digestive system.
   Tehran radio blared readings from the Koran, Islam's holy book
as the country began its 40-day mourning decreed by Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi's Cabinet.
   Khomeini's office did not say when the patriarch will be buried,
but the official Islamic Republic News Agency said ``it will not
take place today (Sunday),'' despite a Moslem tradition to bury the
dead the day they die or the following day at the latest.
   IRNA and the other media did not disclose the immediate cause of
death.
   Iran's 270-seat Parliament convened in an emergency session to
read a political testament Khomeini had written, apparently to
outline how the Islamic republic should be governed after his death.
   The political testament, which the official media in Iran
describe as the ``divine political will and testament,'' was read
during an almost three-hour meeting of Parliament, IRNA said.
   Khomeini's son, Ahmad, 43, was to read the entire 20-page text
later. It was unclear what it contained or whether it named a
successor.
</TEXT>
