<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TonyAwards Bjt   06-04 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tony Awards, Bjt,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Jerome Robbins' Broadway' and `The Heidi Chronicles' Are Tony Favorites</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Awards ceremony begins 9 p.m. EDT. Lead expected by 10 p.m.
and wrapup by 11:45 p.m. Matter below the dash will stand.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' and ``The Heidi
Chronicles'' were the heavy favorites Sunday to win the top 1989
Tony Awards honoring a Broadway season that was short on quality
and quantity, particularly in the area of new musicals.
   ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' the season's biggest hit, received
10 nominations, including best musical. Robbins himself was
nominated as best director of a musical for his work on the show, a
parade of dance numbers from many of his greatest successes,
including ``West Side Story,'' ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' ``Gypsy,''
``The King and I'' and ``Peter Pan.''
   Its minimal competition for best musical were ``Black and
Blue,'' a tap-dancing and blues revue, and ``Starmites,'' a campy,
comic strip adventure.
   ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' Wendy Wasserstein's baby-boom saga,
should add the best play Tony to its list of honors, which already
include the Pulitzer Prize, the New York Drama Critics' Circle
award and the Drama Desk award.
   Also nominated for best play were ``Lend Me a Tenor,'' a farce
by Ken Ludwig about an indisposed opera star; ``Shirley
Valentine,'' a one-woman comedy by Willy Russell about an
unfulfilled English housewife, and ``Largely New York,'' clown Bill
Irwin's wordless entertainment that has him battling video
technology.
   The acting competition is short of big box-office names. Only
ballet dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov, nominated for his transformation
from man to bug in ``Metamorphosis,'' his first stage-acting role,
can be considered a superstar. Also vying for the award for best
actor in a play were Victor Garber and Philip Bosco, both of ``Lend
Me a Tenor,'' and Irwin.
   The best-actress nominees were better known. They included
Madeline Kahn, for playing Billie Dawn in Garson Kanin's classic
``Born Yesterday''; Joan Allen, the heroine of ``The Heidi
Chronicles''; Pauline Collins, who plays the title character in
``Shirley Valentine,'' and Kate Nelligan of ``Spoils of War,''
which closed in December.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The 1988-89 season was a mixed year for Broadway. Although box
office receipts climbed to a record $262 million, attendance
slipped slightly and the number of new productions dropped to 30, a
new low.
   There was a paucity of musicals _ six, compared with 12 the
previous year _ and only ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' generated
much demand at the box office. It also had Broadway's highest
priced ticket _ $55 for an orchestra or front mezzanine seat. Among
the notable flops were ``Legs Diamond,'' ``Chu Chem'' and ``Welcome
to the Club.''
   Recognizing the lack of good musicals, the Tony nominating
committee eliminated two categories _ best book and score of a
musical. ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' and ``Black and Blue''
received more than one nomination in several categories.
   The production of new plays increased to 12, up four from the
1987-88 season, and the number of revivals tripled, from three to
nine.
   But much of Broadway's grosses over the past year were derived
from long-running shows, including ``The Phantom of the Opera,''
``Les Miserables,'' ``Cats,'' ``Anything Goes'' and ``Me and My
Girl.''
   The 43rd annual Tony Awards show, televised live from the
Lunt-Fontanne Theater, was presented by the League of American
Theaters and Producers and the American Theater Wing.
   The winners were selected by 750 members of the theater
community and theater journalists. The Tonys are named for
Antoinette Perry, who was a leading force in the American Theater
Wing during World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
