<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-HongKong     06-04 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Hong Kong,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Thousands Mourn Massacre in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people rallied on a race
track Sunday to mourn the massacre of pro-democracy protesters in
Beijing and denounce the communist government that will take over
this British colony in eight years.
   Two lawmakers, in a protest of the slaughter, announced they
would boycott meetings being held between officials in China and
Hong Kong to arrange the transition to Chinese sovereignity.
   Dissidents also called for a general strike Wednesday to show
sympathy for the suppressed masses in China.
   In Macao, southwest of Hong Kong, an estimated 150,000 residents
_ one-quarter of the population in the Portuguese colony _
demonstrated for four hours, shouting slogans and waving banners
that denounced Li and Chinese senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Many wept at the Hong Kong rally as they watched televised
scenes or listened to news dispatches from the Chinese capital,
where soldiers crushed a pro-democracy sit-in and killed hundreds
of people.
   Some protesters wore black or white clothes, the traditional
Chinese funeral attire, and carried black flags and placards
denouncing the Chinese leadership and the People's Liberation Army.
   Organizers estimated about 200,000 people were at the rally at
the Hong Kong Jockey Club. The demonstrators listened to
pro-democracy speeches, then marched to the central business
district for another rally. Many others joined the march along the
way.
   Several demonstrations have been held in Hong Kong to support
the seven-week series of protests in Beijing. Under an accord, Hong
Kong is to revert to Chinese sovereignty in 1997, and many Hong
Kong residents are worried that this bastion of free trade will be
smothered by communist suppression.
   On May 28, a crowd estimated at about 1.5 million _ one-quarter
of the population _ marched in what was described as the largest
protest rally in the territory's history.
   Hong Kong's residents, 98 percent of them Chinese, have long
been nervous about their future under Chinese rule. The suppression
of the democracy movement has increased their anxiety.
   Under a Sino-British agreement signed in 1984, China promised to
preserve Hong Kong's free-wheeling society and economy for 50 years
under a ``one country, two systems'' concept that would allow
capitalism to exist under communism in a government run by Hong
Kong people without Chinese interference.
   However, Hong Kong's Chinese population, two-thirds of them
refugees from China or their descendants, are skeptical about the
promises.
   At the rally, two outspoken members of the lawmaking Legislative
Council, Martin Lee and Szeto Wah, announced they will not attend
future meetings of a committee drafting a constitution under which
China will rule Hong Kong.
   ``We are not resigning,'' Lee told the rally. ``We have decided
we cannot work for a government which is against the people. We
will not draft the (constitution) until China has a government that
is widely supported by the people.''
   Two other members of the committee, newspaper publisher Louis
Cha and the Anglican Bishop of Hong Kong, Rev. Peter Kwong,
resigned from the committee after Premier Li imposed martial law in
the Chinese capital on May 20.
   The committee is composed of Hong Kong and Chinese officials
appointed by China.
   At the local office of China's official Xinhua News Agency, the
mainland government's unofficial embassy in the British colony,
protesters plastered posters on the wall, including a rebuke of the
People's Liberation Army that said: ``Hey, hey PLA, how many kids
have you killed today?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
