<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Poll-AIDS Bjt   06-04 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-AIDS, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: AIDS Test Confidentiality Opposed in Some Cases</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans oppose the strict confidentiality
of AIDS tests, favoring mandatory notification of spouses and
health officials when the infection is discovered, a national poll
has found.
   Many public health officials say AIDS tests should be kept
confidential to encourage people to be tested. In the poll,
however, 72 percent said the spouse or sexual partner of a person
found to have AIDS should be told.
   Additionally, 67 percent in the Media General-Associated Press
survey said the doctor administering the test should be required to
notify local or state public health officials of a finding of AIDS
infection.
   Mandatory notification of other people or agencies got less
support. Just four in 10 said doctors should have to report
positive tests to the federal government or to insurance companies,
and three in 10 said employers should be told.
   The survey of 1,084 adults was done in advance of the Fifth
International Conference on AIDS, which opened Sunday in Montreal.
It found the disease has touched the lives of a sizable minority of
Americans: Nearly one in five said they personally know someone who
is infected with AIDS or who has died of it.
   Most felt they were at no risk personally of getting AIDS, and
respondents were split on whether AIDS is likely to spread widely
outside known risk groups _ homosexuals and intravenous drug
abusers and their sexual partners.
   Still, majorities said they would pay higher taxes for AIDS
research and treatment. Nearly all favored AIDS education in the
schools, and 81 percent said pupils should be told that using
condoms can prevent AIDS infection.
   The poll also found growing social acceptance of AIDS patients.
Three-quarters said people with AIDS should be entitled to keep
their jobs, and nearly eight in 10 said children who have AIDS
should be admitted to school _ twice as many as held that view in
polls four years ago.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. AIDS is spread most often through sexual
contact, tainted hypodermic needles and infected blood and from
pregnant women to their offspring. An estimated 5 million people
worldwide are infected, and no cure is known.
   Fifty-two percent in the poll thought AIDS was likely to spread
widely beyond current risk groups. At the same time, just 11
percent thought they were at great risk or some risk of getting
AIDS; 23 percent felt ``not much risk'' and 64 percent said ``no
risk at all.'' Two percent were unsure.
   Of those who thought they could get AIDS, three in 10 said they
have changed their sexual behavior to lessen the odds.
   Half overall favored passage of a federal law prohibiting
discrimination against people with AIDS. Other federal efforts won
favor: Six in 10 said they would pay higher taxes for government
spending on AIDS research and 56 percent said would accept a tax
increase for treatment of AIDS patients.
   Eight in 10 said the government should allow AIDS patients to
take experimental drugs that have not been fully tested and
approved as safe. And half favored giving free sterilized needles
to drug abusers if such a move would curb AIDS.
   In most gauges, people ages 18 to 44 supported anti-AIDS efforts
in greater numbers than did their elders. More educated respondents
also were more apt to favor anti-AIDS programs and to accept AIDS
patients at work and school.
   Finally, 55 percent said they would agree to answer detailed
questions about their sexual behavior for a confidential federal
study. The Public Health Service had hoped to study the spread of
AIDS by asking thousands of Americans such questions, but the
survey is being rewritten at the behest of conservative congressmen
who objected to its contents.
   The poll, conducted May 5-13, had a 3-point margin of error.
   Media General Inc., a communications company based in Richmond,
Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in
Charleston, S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
