<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Khomeini     06-04 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Khomeini,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqis Celebrate Khomeini's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqis, who held Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini responsible for the Iran-Iraq war, on Sunday cheered the
news of his death and expressed hope Iran now will sign a peace
treaty to end the war.
   ``We're not rejoicing for his death, but for the 10-year-old
nightmare that is now over,'' said Abdul Karim Subhi, 45, a
schoolteacher.
   Like him, many Iraqis considered Khomeini the main obstacle in
peace talks that have been deadlocked almost since the start of an
Aug. 20 cease-fire that halted fighting in the war.
   Western analysts estimate that 1 million people were killed in
the war, which began in September 1980, the year after Khomeini
came to power.
   Khomeini, 86, died Saturday in a hospital in Tehran. Many Iraqis
who lost family members in the war shouted for joy when Baghdad
Radio reported the news Sunday morning.
   The state radio cut into its normal programs to broadcast cheery
songs in Arabic, but there was no official comment from the
government, which provided refuge to Khomeini part of the time he
lived in exile.
   ``The imposter has perished!'' yelled Um Khalil, a 63-year-old
woman whose son died in the war.
   ``To hell with him,'' she repeated over and over as she ran
around banging on neighbors' doors to tell them the news. Other
families telephoned each other to break the news.
   Iraqis have long blamed Khomeini for keeping the war going even
after Iraq offered peace in 1985. Khomeini did not agree to the
U.N.-mediated cease-fire until July, after a series of battlefield
disasters and a year after Iraq agreed to the cease-fire.
   Iraq invaded Iran on Sept. 20, 1988, but the Iraqis claim Iran
had started the war weeks earlier by shelling border areas after
months of agitation and subversion.
   Iraq's leaders have said that feuding among rival politicians in
Iran has stalled the peace talks.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
doubted Khomeini's death would have any immediate effect on the
talks.
   ``It will take the Iranian leaders at least a few months to
settle their internal struggle before they can discuss the peace
talks,'' one said.
   Khomeini lived in the Shiite Moslem holy city of Najaf, 100
miles south of Baghdad, for about 15 years after he was exiled from
Iran by the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi in 1964.
   But President Saddam Hussein, at the request of the shah,
ordered Khomeini out of Iraq in 1978.
   Khomeini was bitter toward Saddam after that, and the hostility
was seen as one factor in his repeated refusal to end the war.
   Although most of Iraq's 16 million people are Shiite _ like the
overwhelming majority of Iranians _ they rejected Khomeini's
repeated calls to rise up against Saddam, a Sunni Moslem.
   Iraq's official media gave prominent coverage to Khomeini's
illness.
   News of Khomeini's death came too late for Sunday's editions of
Iraqi newspapers.
   But the al-Thawra daily, the newspaper of the ruling Baath
Socialist Party, reported in a front-page headline Sunday:
``Khomeini is on the brink of his grave.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
