<FIRST>r p AM-TexasWomenMayors     06-04 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Women Mayors,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Control Texas' Four Largest City Halls, but Few Have Risen
Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welcome to Texas, where men are men and
women are mayors.
   When Suzie Azar is sworn in June 12 as El Paso mayor, women will
lead Texas' four largest cities. The three largest already have
women mayors: Kathy Whitmire in Houston, Annette Strauss in Dallas
and Lila Cockrell in San Antonio, who took office Thursday,
regaining the post she held from 1975 to 1981.
   They say women's advancement in politics is bringing nearer the
day when voters won't give a candidate's gender a second thought.
   ``I think it's good now that a woman being elected mayor is not
a novelty and that women can do the job and are accepted as such,''
said Ms. Whitmire, who also is president of the Texas Municipal
League and president-elect of the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
   In Dallas, Houston and San Antonio, the mayor's job is
considered part-time and much power rests with the full-time city
managers. But the mayors still have a strong role in leading the
city council and lobbying business and political leaders. In El
Paso, the mayor has more power because there is not a city manager.
   Ann Fears Crawford, author of ``Women in Texas,'' a 1982 book
about female politicians, said the idea of female mayors in Texas
is not what's new.
   ``It's not a sudden spate of women,'' she said. ``We've had them
since the '60s, especially in small towns.
   ``What you're just seeing now is them working up to metropolitan
areas.''
   Women are mayors of 12 of the 100 largest cities in the United
States, according to the Center for American Women and Politics at
Rutgers University, and five of those 12 are in Texas. Betty Turner
is mayor of Corpus Christi, the nation's 58th-largest city.
   ``Women have a reputation of caring more about social and
`compassion' issues,'' said Sue Tolleson Rinehart, associate
professor of political science at Texas Tech. ``In local politics,
that's what you tend to be thinking about.''
   But if Texas voters are willing to send women to city hall, they
haven't yet been willing to send them to many higher offices. Of
the 181 seats in the state Legislature, only 19 are held by women.
Treasurer Ann Richards is the only woman in a statewide elected
office, and the state's 29-member congressional delegation is all
male.
   ``It is true that women are making slightly more progress at the
municipal level, but not a lot more,'' said Ms. Whitmire.
   The chairmen of the Texas Democratic and Republican parties said
they believe women are working their way up in state politics.
   ``It's a lot like anything else,'' state GOP Chairman Fred Meyer
said. ``You have to work your way up the ranks.
   ``You don't just run for Congress _ you have to be on the school
board, be on city council, be a mayor, be a state representative.
You have to be something first, because it's not a job for
amateurs.''
   Bob Slagle, chairman of the Texas Democratic Party, said he
believes there is a relationship between women's rise in business
and politics.
   ``Women are demonstrating they are capable in the corporate and
political worlds,'' Slagle said. ``You get away from a lot of the
myths that women are different from men and can't handle making
decisions and running things.''
   Ms. Whitmire said women are more likely to rise faster in
politics than in business because ``voters tend to be more
open-minded'' than corporate executives.
   The next logical step for women in Texas politics would be to
have a female governor _ the first since Miriam A. ``Ma'' Ferguson
was elected in 1924 as a puppet candidate for her husband,
impeached ex-Gov. James Ferguson.
   Ms. Richards, who gained national attention last year as the
keynote speaker at the Democratic National Convention, is expected
to run for governor next year. Ms. Rinehart said the treasurer's
reputation for toughness is deserved.
   ``The Texas political culture has had the reputation of being so
hard on women that the ones who do survive tend to be superwomen,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
