<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--ViolinContest     06-04 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Violin Contest,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Musician Wins Queen Elisabeth Violin Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young Soviet musician won the Queen
Elisabeth international violin contest Sunday and will receive
$7,000 in cash and a lucrative contract for concerts throughout
Europe.
   Vadim Repin edged out another 17-year-old musician, Akiko
Suwanai of Japan, in the grueling competition that lasted a month.
They were the two youngest contestants.
   Evgueni Bouchkov of the Soviet Union was third, and Erez Ofer of
Israel finished fourth. West German Ulrike-Anima Mathe took fifth
place followed by Catherine Cho, of Ann Arbor, Mich.
   Twelve finalists performed works of Mozart, Beethoven, Brahms
and Debussy together with Belgium's National Orchestra at the Beaux
Arts Palace throughout the week to decide the $37,300 in prizes.
   The competition began in early May with 53 violinists.
</TEXT>
