<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-04 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling Duels Break Out Across Beirut, Five Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners unleashed
artillery barrages across the city Sunday, wounding 14 civilians
and ending a three-week relative lull in the latest round of
Lebanon's civil war.
   Police said five civilians were wounded when shells struck
Moslem west Beirut's Hamra commercial district and the seaside
regions of Raouche and Ein Mreisseh.
   Nine civilians were hospitalized in Christian east Beirut when
Syrian gunners pounded that side of the divided capital, police
said.
   They were the first shelling casualties since May 11, when the
Arab League called a cease-fire to halt nine weeks of fierce
artillery duels. At least 360 people have died and 1,410 have been
wounded since fighting broke out March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's
mostly Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian and Druse Moslem
militiamen.
   In Hamra, Sunday strollers ran for cover as a three-shell salvo
crashed near a cluster of sidewalk cafes. Cars sped off, blaring
their horns.
   Along the Moslem coast, sunbathers fled crowded beaches as
radios warned people to stay indoors.
   Aoun's command said its gunners pounded Beirut's Moslem sector
to avenge what it called ``escalated Syrian bombardment of east
Beirut and other population centers'' in the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   The Syrians shelled the Christian-controlled port and the coast
north of Beirut, a police spokesman said.
   The command of the 40,000 Syrian troops stationed in Lebanon
under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate declined comment on Aoun's charge.
   It was the first time both sides had shelled residential
districts since the Arab League cease-fire was called.
   ``Whether it's just a message to the Arab summit troika or the
beginning of an all-out new shelling round remains to be seen,''
said a police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules.
   He referred to a meeting in Rabat, Morocco of the three-member
Arab League committee comprised of King Hassan II of Morocco, King
Fahd of Saudi Arabia and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid.
   Arab leaders meeting last month in Casablanca set up the
committee to stabilize the May 11 truce and find a political
settlement to Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   The latest round of fighting broke out after Aoun blockaded
militia-run ports south of Beirut to recover lost taxes estimated
at $100 million annually. Militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Popular Socialist Party responded by shelling Christian
districts. They were joined by Syrian gunners.
   In the southern port of Tyre, a 33-pound explosive went off
Sunday under a black Mercedes parked on a main highway, wrecking
the car but causing no casualties, police said. The explosion
occurred 25 yards from the logistics center of the United Nations
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon.
   Also in Tyre, four civilians were wounded when they were caught
in a cross fire between Palestinian gunmen and Shiite Moslem Amal
militiamen, police said.
   The Amal militiamen were in a yacht off the Rashidiyeh refugee
camp, while the Palestinians were inside their camp.
   Police said they had no information on what triggered the
shootout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
