<HEAD>With AM-Judicial Finances Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a profile of the personal finances of
the federal judiciary, based on an Associated Press computerized
analysis of 935 financial disclosure reports covering 1987, the
most recent complete set available.
   The figures are medians, meaning half the judges are above that
and half are below. The figures are derived independently. For
example, the net value of investments was computed individually for
each judge and then ranked to produce a median.
   The forms allow the judges to report income and assets within
wide numerical ranges.
   The median figures:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NET VALUE OF INVESTMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   High: $350,000; Low: $140,024
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TOTAL OUTSIDE INCOME</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   High: $39,500; Low: $16,624
   From Investments: High: $29,627; Low: $10,002
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INVESTMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   High: $400,000; Low: $157,008 (The value of homes and some other
assets are exempt from disclosure.)
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OVERALL STATISTICS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Active judges: 702
   Senior judges: 233 (only those who worked at least 60 days)
   
   District judges: 715
   Appellate judges: 211
   Supreme Court justices: 9
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CURRENT SALARIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Chief justice: $115,000
   Associate justice: $110,000
   Appeals judge: $95,000
   District judge: $89,500
</TEXT>
