<FIRST>r i AM-Deng     06-04 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deng,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng, Under Treatment For Cancer, Ordered Attack On Beijing, Sources
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping gave the orders for
the military assault on central Beijing from a hospital where he is
being treated for prostate cancer, official sources said Sunday.
   The sources said Deng's condition is serious. He has long been
rumored to have prostate problems, and there have been unconfirmed
reports he has cancer.
   The officials, in the office of former President Li Xiannian,
said Deng gave the orders Saturday for troops to crush the protest
in Tiananmen Square. The military assault killed hundreds of
people. Li is now the head of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, an important advisory body.
   ``Even if they're functioning out of ignorance they are still
participating and must be suppressed,'' Deng was quoted as saying.
``In China, even 1 million people can be considered a small sum.''
   Up to 1 million people streamed into Beijing streets in recent
weeks to support the students' democracy movements.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Deng was
angry, saying he had not been properly informed about the student
movement.
   Deng, 84, heads the Central Military Commission, his only public
post after resigning from most of his official offices in 1987.
Deng, China's most influential advocate for economic reform, has
opposed rapid political change.
   Deng reportedly forced the resignation of Communist Party
General Secretary Zhao Ziyang because of his conciliatory reaction
to the student protesters. But there has been no official word on
Zhao, whose resignation would have to be accepted by the Communist
Party's Central Committee.
