<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Homecoming     06-04 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Homecoming,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian-American Returns to Tragic Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago, Yan Ke fled the Khmer
Rouge killing fields, evaded an advancing Vietnamese army and was
put in fetid refugee camps. He said he never expected to see his
homeland or family again.
   With a little nephew in tow, the refugee ended his odyssey in
the United States _ haunted by the past and concerned about
survival in a strange land.
   But Yan Ke did well and recently was able to join an increasing
number of his countrymen cautiously returning for visits from the
United States, France, Australia and Canada. Rather than crossing
border minefields, this time he traveled on airliners from
Columbus, Ohio, to Phnom Penh.
   His aging parents and nearly 40 family members were waiting for
him.
   ``When I stepped off the plane and they were all there, I could
say nothing,'' Yan Ke said. ``And I nearly cried when I saw my
ruined country. They need everything.''
   Three generations posed for his video camera within the former
Royal Palace compound _ a haven of peace before the Cambodian war,
Khmer Rouge terror, Vietnamese invasion and civil strife.
   Yan Ke said he was a high school student in the northwestern
province of Battambang when Khmer Rouge guerrillas routed the
U.S.-backed government in 1975.
   Like many strong tee-agers, he was separated from his parents
and said he was assigned to a work brigade. Reward for labor in the
fields amounted to several spoonfuls of rice mixed with water and
vegetable scraps.
   An uncle, a cousin and several other relatives were among the
hundreds of thousands killed by the Khmer Rouge, Yan Ke said.
   At night he would listen to victims being taken away to the
killing fields and hear the thud of blunt instruments against human
flesh. Yan Ke said he still has nightmares about one boy from his
brigade who kept a shoulder bag he had found in the forest. This
``criminal'' was brought before the workers; then his throat was
cut and his stomach slit open.
   In 1979, with Vietnamese troops invading, Yan Ke said his family
held a futive family reunion. It was decided that he and a
3-year-old nephew, Voeun Ke, would try to make it to the Thai
frontier. Another brother and two sisters would remain to care for
the parents.
   He and his nephew reached the border after three days of
walking, Yan Ke said, but robbers took the bits of gold he had
concealed in a pack of cigarettes.
   For more than a year, Yan Ke and his nephew lived in swelling
refugee camps in Thailand and the Philippines. Then, with the help
of a Roman Catholic charity, they arrived in the United States and
in 1981 settled in Columbus, where 2,500 other Cambodians have
found homes.
   Yan Ke said he worked as a machine operator in a steel mill,
then got a job with the state employment office. He also earned a
bachelor's degree in computer science and developed a home repair
business.
   Still single, he and his nephew live in one of four apartments
that he owns. ``It was tough being a father without any experience,
but I've learned,'' Yan Ke said. His nephew prefers hamburgers to
rice and is forgetting the Cambodian language.
   Like many Cambodians and other Indochinese refugees, Yan Ke sent
thousands of dollars to his relatives. Recently he decided to see
them again.
   ``Some of my Cambodian friends said I was crazy, and the U.S.
State Department warned that they could not help me if I got into
trouble,'' Yan Ke said.
   But he also knew Cambodians had been returning over the past 18
months, and the government, hoping to attact tourism and
investment, had encouraged them. Despite recent liberalization and
prospects of a settlement of the Cambodian conflict, a communist
party is still in control within and Khmer Rouge guerrillas are
still mobilized.
   ``Many still don't trust the situation,'' he said. ``But I'd
like overseas Cambodians to become more involved in helping the
people here. Especially the children.''
   Yan Ke visited schools without books and clinics with few
supplies. He plans to raise money in Ohio to help a clinic.
   ``It's enough suffering. We need a break,'' Yan Ke said one
night in Phnom Penh. ``Look at those who were born in in the Khmer
Rouge era and weren't as lucky as my nephew. They have only seen
the dark side of life.''
</TEXT>
