<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     06-04 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>House To Install New Speaker, Then Turn To S&amp;L Bailout Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House is expected to install new speaker
this week and then turn to one of the biggest pieces of legislation
of the year, a bailout of the troubled savings and loan industry.
   The Senate hopes to finish work on its version of a bill that
started off as mostly an emergency increase in veterans spending,
but which has become a menagerie of lawmakers' pet priorities.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, beset by ethics charges, announced
last week he would relinquish his gavel upon the selection of a
successor.
   Democrats on Tuesday plan to caucus and nominate Thomas S.
Foley, D-Wash., currently the majority leader, for that job. The
full House will ratify the nomination later in the day.
   The House will then take up President Bush's proposal for joint
development of a fighter jet with Japan.
   A Senate vote last month already made it clear the project known
as the FSX will go forward, but House opponents want a chance to
vote on what they say amounts to the United States giving away
technology that made America the world's leading aircraft
manufacturer.
   Prime Minister Bhutto of Pakistan is scheduled to address a
joint meeting of Congress on Wednesday.
   The House is scheduled to begin debate later Wednesday on its
version of Bush's plan to revamp and keep solvent the savings and
loan industry.
   The massive legislation rejects the president's notion that its
$50 billion in costs should be hidden from the taxpayers by keeping
them ``off-budget.'' The Senate, in its version, went along with
Bush's budget scheme, even though the overall costs are several
billion dollars higher in the long term because the complex
off-budget mechanism would mean higher interest payments.
   The legislation includes measures designed to more carefully
control the thrift industry to avoid future calamities. The
financial institutions have lobbied hard to minimize those new
restrictions.
   The Senate has been bogged down on a tiny piece of legislation
compared to the S&amp;L matter _ a $3.3 billion-and-growing
supplemental spending bill for the remainder of fiscal 1989.
   The White House warned that emergency spending was needed before
Memorial Day to keep veterans health programs from running out of
money, but the deadline passed without calamity.
   So the Senate plans on Tuesday to spend a third day loading up
the bill with whatever favored amendments senators can offer and
win.
   After last week's work, the bill includes such items as aid to
apple farmers whose sales have been hurt by consumers reluctant to
digest fruit sprayed with the chemical Alar, and aid to Kansas
farmers hurt by drought.
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
whose committee produced the bill, included $75 million to rebuild
a 100-yard-wide radio telescope in West Virginia that collapsed
last year, and several other more earthly projects for his home
state.
   Not all amemdnets are pork barrel, and some are controversial.
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., plans an amendment this week to delay a
portion of the new catastrophic illness insurance program.
   There is little controversy over the basics of the bill. It
provides $1.2 billion for veterans programs, including health care,
which need a cash influx to carry them until the end of the fiscal
year. Extra money is also provided for student loans, food stamps,
and the cost of fighting the forest fires last year in the West.
   The House has already approved its version of the spending bill.
The two chambers must settle on identical bills before the measure
can go to the president.
   Despite the busy legislative week, there will be considerable
behind-the-scenes action in the House. Foley, the No. 2 man, is a
sure bet to be smoothly installed as speaker, but the ethics
controversy also has claimed Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif.,
who announced he'll step down rather than face an inquiry like the
one endured by Wright.
   With Foley moving up to speaker, that leaves the Democrats with
both their No. 2 and No. 3 slots to fill. An election on those is
expected next week and prominent Democrats are fighting for
position.
   Reps. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., are
competing for the majority leader post.
   The whip's race is a four-way contest between Reps. William H.
Gray III, D-Pa., Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., David Bonior, D-Mich., and
Henry Waxman, D-Calif.
   Gray spoke out sharply last week after news reports, citing
unnamed Justice Department sources, said the congressman or members
of his staff were under investigation.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Sunday called ``absolutely
false'' charges that the Justice Department has become politicized
and that senior officials there deliberately leaked the information
to embarrass Gray.
   ``I have directed that every resource that we have in the
Department of Justice be brought to bear on the investigation of
the leaks,'' Thornburgh said on the CBS program ``Face the Nation.''
</TEXT>
