<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-PolandElectionataGlance     06-04 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland Election at a Glance,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look at Poland Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are facts and figures on Poland's parliamentary and Senate
elections Sunday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHAT'S AT STAKE _ Of 460 seats in the Sejm, or parliament, 161 _
or 35 percent _ are open to opposition candidates. The remaining
299 are set aside for members of the Communist Party and its
allies. All the seats are contested, except for a ``national list''
of 35 positions for which the communist coalition selected
unopposed candidates.
   There are 1,745 candidates nationwide for the 425 contested
seats.
   In the newly created Senate, all 100 seats are freely contested,
making it the first fully democratically picked legislative chamber
in the East bloc. There are 553 candidates nationwide for those
seats.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VOTING _ The polls will be open from 6 a.m. to 10 p.m. There
will be 22,411 polling places in Poland and about 205 abroad,
mainly at Polish diplomatic posts and construction projects.
   There are 27,211,188 eligible voters, according to the
government. Voters must be 18. If they live abroad, they must
provide proof of Polish citizenship.
   Voters cast ballots by crossing out all names on the ballot
except that of the chosen candidate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VICTORY MARGIN _ Candidates must receive more than half of the
votes. If none does, the two candidates receiving the most ballots
will participate in run-off elections June 18.
   The candidates on the ``national list'' in the uncontested races
also must receive more than 50 percent of the votes. If they do
not, their seats will not be filled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
