<DOCNO> AP890604-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-D-DayJump     06-04 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D-Day Jump,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Paratroopers Reenact Beginning Of D-Day Invasion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STE. MERE EGLISE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In brilliant sunshine and a
stiff wind, hundreds of American paratroopers floated onto a field
in Normandy on Sunday to commemorate the jump made by the first
Allied troops on D-Day 45 years ago.
   Thousands of people gazed skyward as eight C-130 transport
planes circled overhead and 450 members of the 82nd Airborne from
Fort Bragg, N.C., and the 3rd Battalion, 325th Infantry of
Vincenza, Italy, tumbled from planes.
   ``It was windy, fast, the speed was exhilarating,'' said Sgt.
John Thomas of Freeport, N.Y., with the 82nd, known as the
``All-Americans.''
   Some of Thomas' buddies were less thrilled with the wind-driven
drop, and at least one paratrooper was injured, suffering a broken
arm.
   Spec. Mike Herman of Stamford, Conn. collided with another
paratrooper about 150 feet off the ground but was not injured.
   ``I landed a foot from the river with a face full of canopy,''
the 21-year-old paratrooper said. ``Of course I'd heard a lot of
stories about jumping here _ about church steeples and rivers and
trees _ and we knew we were in for a rough time.''
   But the demonstration jump was easy compared to the one made in
the pre-dawn darkness of June 6, 1944. Then, 1,500 American
paratroopers jumped behind enemy lines a few hours before the
seaborne assault that signaled the end of Adolf Hitler's Nazi
Germany.
   ``You could see the ground fire coming up on the paratroopers
from the Germans in Ste. Mere, red burning traces tearing through
the air. The men were clearly visible, their parachutes shining in
the moonlight,'' recalled retired Army Maj. Lewis Allen of
Fayetteville, Ark., who as a pathfinder jumped about 30 minutes
ahead of the other paratroopers on D-Day.
   While Allen watched the men being picked from the sky, more than
180,000 troops were moving across the English Channel for the
greatest amphibious assault in history.
   The invasion of Normandy's beaches, known as Operation Overlord,
began at dawn on June 6. Three million American, Canadian and
British soldiers collected in England and later reinforced the
troops who opened up a 50-mile stretch of coastline on D-Day.
   Lively and solemn ceremonies will be held over three days to
honor the Allied forces and the 367,000 soldiers who were killed or
wounded in the battle.
   It all began in Ste. Mere Eglise, with paratroopers falling like
confetti from the sky, landing in trees, in cemeteries and even on
the church steeple in an episode dramatized in the film, ``The
Longest Day.''
   The village was a crucial link between Cherbourg and Bayeux, the
bridgehead that blocked three German divisions in the North,
shielded the landing beaches only five miles away and enabled the
Americans to seal off the Contentin Peninsula within two weeks.
   ``This place meant a hell of a lot,'' Allen said, as he
autographed the back of a little French girl's jacket. ``I'm proud
of what we did, and I'm proud to be back.''
</TEXT>
