<FILEID>AP-NR-06-04-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ActressAttack     06-04 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Attack,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Threats, Prison Releasing Attacker Next Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Theresa Saldana is terrified that a
crazed fan who nearly butchered her seven years ago will try to
finish his deadly ``divine mission'' after he is released from
prison next week.
   Threatening letters that wild-eyed Scottish drifter Arthur
Jackson have written to the actress have been unceasing over the
years; prison authorities cannot stop his mail. And even though
federal authorities will deport Jackson upon his release, they
agree there is nothing stopping him from returning.
   Jackson, 53, has a long history of psychiatric problems and has
been under the care of a psychiatrist in prison. But he was given a
June 15 parole date for good behavior after serving seven years of
a 12-year sentence for the vicious March 15, 1982, attack. In
California, inmates automatically earn one day off their sentence
for every day served without trouble.
   ``Threats are not considered grounds to keep a person in prison.
You have to act on the threats,'' said Deputy District Attorney
Michael E. Knight, who prosecuted Jackson.
   In a letter to Saldana after the attack, Jackson said he
regretted using a knife on her because ``a gun would have given me
a better chance of reunion with you in heaven.''
   ``It is just unbelievable that he is getting out,'' said Miss
Saldana, 34. ``I feel like I am in a nightmare. I really feel my
rights are being overlooked. Why is it life, liberty and the
pursuit of happiness is being taken from me?''
   ``We know he will attempt to carry out his threats,'' said
Knight. ``But we have no way to protect her unless he tries to
carry out his threats. It doesn't speak very well for a society
that is supposed to protect the rights of all people.''
   Miss Saldana, a newlywed who is five months pregnant, said, ``It
terrifies me he will be in the streets of Europe with no
supervision.''
   Jackson spent a year in a Scottish psychiatric hospital after a
nervous breakdown at age 17. He crossed the Atlantic and joined the
U.S. Army in 1955, then suffered another mental collapse that
landed him in an Army hospital for psychiatric care.
   Jackson was discharged from the Army after a suicide attempt and
later deported to Scotland following his arrest in 1961 for
allegedly threatening President John F. Kennedy.
   He became obsessed with Miss Saldana after watching her films,
including ``Raging Bull'' and ``I Want to Hold Your Hand,'' and his
diaries revealed he thought he was on a ``divine mission'' and
could win the actress by ``sending her into eternity.'' In 1982, he
entered the United States illegally to hunt her down.
   Jackson attacked Miss Saldana outside her apartment, stabbing
her 10 times and bending the blade of his kitchen knife with the
force of his blows.
   ``I will never forget the searing, ghastly pain, the grotesque
and devastating experience of this person nearly butchering me to
death, or the bone-chilling sight or my own blood splattered
everywhere,'' Saldana told the judge in a 1984 resentencing
statement. Resentencing hearings are held when changes in
sentencing laws may affect an inmate.
   Since the attack, Miss Saldana has become a spokeswoman for
victims' rights and did a television movie about the case,
``Victims for Victims.'' She also has recently completed an action
movie, ``Angel Town.''
   Fan fanatics are not new to the show business world, but the
Saldana attack was one of the most vicious in recent memory.
   ``It isn't a case of one actress and one crazy fan. These
threats happen to others _ chronic, persistent threats. I know
other celebrities who have been threatened,'' said Miss Saldana.
   She wouldn't name names, but an obsessed fan currently faces
trial in Los Angeles on charges of threatening ``Family Ties'' TV
star Michael J. Fox and his family with death. In Connecticut, an
emotionally disturbed woman posing as the wife of talk show host
David Letterman has broken into his house several times. And in
1980, former Beatle John Lennon was shot to death near his New York
City apartment by a disturbed admirer.
   Like Miss Saldana, the delivery man who saved her life by
stopping Jackson's attack is furious about the impending release.
   ``Actually, I don't think he should even be deported. I feel he
should be here in jail for the rest of his life,'' said Jeff Fenn,
who quit his water company delivery job after the attack and became
a deputy sheriff.
   Fenn also has gotten 40 letters from Jackson, but doesn't feel
threatened.
   ``I don't see him coming after me. Now I've got a gun. I didn't
have one then,'' he said. ``He said his mission wasn't finished and
I got in his way.''
</TEXT>
