<FIRST>r i AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0736 06-04 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0736,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Death May Speed Up OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `OPEC officials ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with private talks Sunday, comment. A longer version also moved on financial
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's oil minister said Sunday that a
key OPEC meeting will be sped up so he can return to Tehran for the
funeral of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was
scheduled to open a formal meeting Monday to plan its pricing and
production strategy for the rest of the year.
   Analysts expect OPEC to set a new elevated production output cap
of 19.5 million or 20 million barrels a day, a level that would
likely hold prices at current levels and do little to gasoline
prices at the pump.
   Khomeini's death Saturday raised questions about the cartel's
work schedule. Iran, a large crude oil producer, is a leading
member of the organization.
   Gholamreza Aqazadeh, the Iranian oil chief, said government
officials were not requiring that he return to Iran. But he said he
wanted to return ``to be with my people in Iran and participate in
the funeral ceremony.''
   He said the other oil ministers were discussing the situation.
   ``I think due to the circumstances, the conference will end
sooner than expected,'' he said through an interpreter.
   OPEC officials began preliminary discussions Friday on pricing
and production goals for the last six months of the year. On
Sunday, the ministers met privately in their rooms to try to
arrange a deal.
   ``We still have a way to go,'' said Libyan Oil Minister Fawzi
Shakshuki.
   The ministers appear ready to boost their production ceiling,
now at 18.5 million barrels a day, with a target price of $18 a
barrel.
   Aqazadeh said he expected demand for OPEC oil to grow about 1
million barrels a day in the last six months of the year, implying
the cartel might lift its ceiling to at least 19.5 million barrels
daily.
   He said deciding how the increase should be distributed among
the producers ``is our main problem.'' He declined to elaborate,
saying only, ``I think we will reach an agreement.''
   Oil prices have soared since the ministers late last year
slashed output in the first six months of 1989. The average price
of a basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC is nearly $17.70 a
barrel, more than 43 percent higher than in late November.
   OPEC members are: Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
