<FIRST>r w AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0763 06-04 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 3 grafs new with Bush back at White House; no further comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Returning to Washington With Full Foreign Policy Plate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush returned to the White House
from a 10-day trip on Sunday, faced with new foreign policy
challenges stemming from the bloody military crackdown in China and
the death of Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   On the flight from Maine to Washington, White House spokesman
Bob Hall told reporters that the president was being updated
regularly on developments by Robert Gates, his deputy national
security adviser.
   Hall said Bush had no meetings or appointments planned at the
White House on Sunday. On Monday, he will meet with bipartisan
leaders of Congress in a session that had been scheduled before the
bloodbath in China and the death of Khomeini.
   Bush made no public comment on the death of the 89-year-old
radical Iranian leader, who had branded the United States as the
devil.
   A White House statement said, ``With his passing, we hope Iran
will now move toward assuming a responsible role in the
international community.''
   Bush spent two days at his seaside estate at Kennebunkport,
Maine, driving his speedboat, fishing and jogging, after returning
from a week-long trip to Italy, Belgium, West Germany and England
and a NATO summit.
   The president initially appeared unaware of Khomeini's death,
announced shortly before midnight Saturday.
   Jogging near his seaside home at 6:30 a.m. EDT, Bush was asked
by a reporter whether he had heard about Khomeini. When Bush
replied, ``No,'' the reporter shouted that the ayatollah had died.
   The president declined to comment. He also brushed aside
questions about China, where hundreds of people were reported
killed in a crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Bush was asked about Khomeini and China again when he attended
Sunday services with his wife, Barbara, at First Congregational
Church of Kennebunkport, where they frequently worship.
   He made no comment, other than to point out the White House had
issued a statement about Khomeini.
   The White House issued a separate statement Saturday night in
Bush's name about China. It said, ``I deeply deplore the decision
to use force against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss
of life.''
   Urging Beijing to use nonviolent tactics, Bush said, ``I hope
that China will rapidly return to the path of political and
economic reform and conditions of stability so that this
relationship (between the United States and China), so important to
both our peoples, can continue its growth.''
   The president and his wife were greeted on a first-name basis at
the church by the Rev. Robert Howes, who informed the congregation
he was retiring as pastor.
   He also told Bush, ``All of us are filled with new hopes and
confidence because of the work you have just completed in Europe.''
He said the president's efforts made the world a safer place.
   At the NATO summit, Bush proposed that the United States and
Soviet Union reduce combat troops in Europe to 275,000 on each side
and make other cuts in conventional forces.
   He also helped engineer a settlement of a dispute on short-range
nuclear missiles.
   Mrs. Bush, talking to the congregation, recalled her visit last
Sunday to a church in Nettuno, Italy, near a cemetery where
Americans are buried from World War II.
   ``We went to this little church, didn't understand a word (of
the Italian service), but we understood the spirit _ the same
family spirit that we have here.''
</TEXT>
