<FIRST>u w AM-US-ForeignPolicy 2ndLd-Writethru a0788 06-04 1048</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Foreign Policy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0788,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pushed to Act on China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new to include Fitzwater comments; picks up 6th
graf previous ``Solarz''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal and conservative congressional leaders
both demanded Sunday that President Bush end military aid to China
in retaliation for the government's bloody suppression of
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., warned that unless Bush takes a
stronger stand on China, ``Congress will do it for him.''
   The president, who spent the weekend relaxing at his
Kennebunkport, Maine, home, brushed off reporters' questions about
the blood-letting as he took an early morning jog on Sunday.
   Upon his return to the White House, the president again chose to
offer no response to reporters' queries about the crisis.
   In Washington, leading members of the president's own party
demanded action.
   Rep. Mickey Edwards of Oklahoma, chairman of the House
Republican Policy Committee, criticized what he called the
administration's ``excessively cautious'' reaction to the military
crackdown in Beijing.
   ``Diplomatic messages of disapproval are a pretty puny reaction
to the murdering of innocent civilians, whose only crime is to want
the same freedoms we in the West take for granted,'' Edwards said
in a statement issued by his office.
   ``The Defense Department, the State Department and the Commerce
Department ought to act immediately, in unison, to put some
substance into the U.S. condemnations,'' he said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Sunday a State
Department task force has been mulling over policy options for the
president, adding, ``there is no indication of what direction we
might go, or when he would get the specific options.''
   Asked about demands for cuts in U.S. military aid, Fitzwater
said the administration did not ``want to act precipitously. We
want to make sure that our response is correct.''
   ``There are a number of ways that the United States government
can express itself in this matter. It's appropriate that we act in
the right fashion and not too quickly,'' Fitzwater said. ``We'll
consider all the options and choose an appropriate course when the
time is right.''
   Solarz, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Asian
subcommittee, and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., ranking GOP member of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, expressed outrage at the
violent turn of events in Beijing and demanded a review of the
U.S.-China relationship.
   ``I think it would be politically unacceptable and morally
unthinkable ... for us to continue to sell arms to a country that
is engaged in the wanton slaughter of its own people,'' Solarz said.
   Helms, who vowed to ask the Senate on Monday to approve such a
step, said he believes there is ``strong bipartisan support'' for
the move.
   Indeed, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of Foreign
Relations subcommittee on East Asian and Pacific affairs, also
called for a halt to all military assistance and cooperation with
the People's Republic, saying U.S.-Chinese relations had been dealt
``a bloody blow.''
   But Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., another member of the Senate
panel, advised a cautious approach, approving of Bush's ``calm and
stable'' response to the situation.
   ``He ought to keep our ambassador there ... we ought to keep
maintain our agreements (to supply aid),'' Lugar said on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press.'' The senator said the U.S. leverage in the
matter is ``always very limited. There are some situations we
really cannot control.''
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, who helped forge the
first U.S. ties to China during President Nixon's term, also
advised that the president ``can't afford emotional outbursts'' in
the present situation.
   Appearing on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,''
Kissinger said he was ``appalled'' by the events in Beijing but
cautioned that the United States must be ``very careful''' about
considering cutting ties with the Chinese in order not to give the
Soviet Union ``a free ride'' in influence in Asia.
   But Solarz appeared to be unsatisfied by Bush's statement on
Saturday, calling for ``nonviolence, restraint and dialogue.''
Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in a Saturday television
appearance, called the events ``extremely deplorable'' and said the
U.S. government was ``disturbed'' by the violent turn of events.
   ``I think we have to manifest our concern over what happened in
China by deeds as well as words. It's simply not sufficient to say
that we are disturbed by what happened,'' Solarz said on CBS-TV's
``Face The Nation.''
   ``We have to make it clear that the United States will not
continue to conduct business as usual with a government that
engages in the wanton slaughter of its own people. And I have to
say that if the president doesn't take the initiative in changing
American policy in this regard, the Congress will do it for him,''
Solarz said.
   The U.S.-Chinese relationship has blossomed on economic,
military and political fronts since formal diplomatic relations
were established in 1979.
   Since that time, the United States has sold more than $748
million in arms to China, most recently a $100 million deal in
which Beijing purchased six Chinook CH-47D helicopters manufactured
by Boeing Co.
   China, with U.S. approval, also reached a $245 million agreement
with Grumman Corp. in 1987 under which the U.S. company improved
the avionics of China's F-8 fighter jet.
   ``We never should have gotten into the business of supplying
arms to any communist country,'' Helms said, adding he wanted to
``cut off all that sort of thing.''
   Helms, a longtime foe of relations with Communist China, said
``the (China) military needs to understand that there will be a
harsh reaction'' if the violence continues.
   Besides calling for the immediate return of Ambassador James
Lilley, Solarz sad the United States should consider a suspension
of trade in high-technology items, and a change in immigration
regulations to allow those Chinese students now in America who
supported the democratic movement to remain here until it is clear
they won't be punished upon their return.
   The State Department has set up a round-the-clock desk to
monitor the situation in China.
   One official confirmed that the Chinese Ambassador, Han Xu, had
been called into the State Department on Saturday to hear the U.S.
expression of ``deep concern'' about the violent developments in
China.
   U.S. officials are ``in constant touch'' with Chinese officials
in Beijing and Washington, the official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
